1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Qd2 Ng4 $5 {
An interesting attepmt to avoid the well-known theoretical lines.} ({More
common moves here are} 7... Qc7) (7... Bb4) 8. Bg5 Qc7 (8... Qb6 9. Nb3 f6 10.
Bf4 Bb4 11. Bg3 O-O 12. h3 Nge5 13. f4 Nf7 14. O-O-O $14 {with a space
advantage for White in Tologontegin-Kachar, Kaluga 2007.}) 9. Nxc6 (9. Nb3 Bd6
$5 10. f4 $2 h6 11. e5 Bxe5 12. fxe5 Qxe5+ 13. Be2 hxg5 14. O-O-O Nf2 {0-1
Zambrana-Sunye Neto, Sao Paulo (zt) 2007}) 9... bxc6 10. h3 (10. f3 Ne5 11. Be3
Rb8 12. O-O-O {could be an alternative.}) 10... Ne5 11. O-O-O Rb8 12. Be3 Qa5
13. Bd4 ({White can insert} 13. Ba7 $5 Rb7 14. Bd4) 13... Ng6 ({Also} 13... f6
$5 {was interesting} 14. f4 Nf7 {as the black knight on f7 is not vulnerable
compared to g6.}) 14. f4 e5 15. fxe5 Be7 (15... Nxe5 16. Bxa6 $1 Be7 (16...
Bxa6 17. Bxe5) 17. Bxc8 O-O (17... Bg5 18. Qxg5 Nd3+ 19. Rxd3 Qxg5+ 20. Be3 $18
) 18. Nd5 Qxa2 19. Nxe7+ Kh8 20. Qc3 {and Black has no} Nc4 {due to} 21. Bxg7#)
16. Kb1 Bb4 $5 17. Ka1 $6 ({During the game I was more worried about} 17. a3 $5
Bxa3 18. Na2 Qxd2 (18... Qc7 19. e6 fxe6 20. Bxg7 Rg8 21. Bc3 $13) 19. Rxd2 Be7
$13) 17... O-O 18. Bc4 c5 $1 {Black gains an important tempo to finish his
development and continue the pressure on White's king position.} 19. Bf2 Nxe5
20. Bd5 Bb7 21. Bxb7 $2 {Underestimating Black's attack.} (21. Be1 d6 22. Rf1 {
and White would still be in the game.}) 21... Nc4 22. Qd5 (22. Qd3 Nxb2 23.
Qxa6 Bxc3 24. Qxa5 Nxd1+ 25. Qxc3 Nxc3 $19) 22... Nxb2 $1 23. Kxb2 Bxc3+ 24.
Kb1 Qb4+ 25. Qb3 Rxb7 26. Bxc5 (26. Kc1 {would allow a nice finish after} Rfb8
27. Rd3 Qa3+ $1) 26... Qxe4 27. Bxf8 Kxf8 28. Rxd7 Rxb3+ 29. axb3 Bf6 0-1

